        "No worker thread utilization metric (active/queued requests)",
        "No circuit breaker state metric for Stripe",
        "No fraud detection error rate or outcome breakdown metric",
        "No payment latency end-to-end histogram (only component-level histograms)",
        "No queue depth or request backlog metric",
        "No metric for payments that succeeded at Stripe but failed to persist to DB"
      ]
    },
    "tracing": {
      "coverage": "No distributed tracing mentioned",
      "gaps": [
        "Cannot trace a payment request across fraud-check → stripe → DB write",
        "Cannot correlate a Stripe charge ID with a fraud check decision and DB transaction ID",
        "On-call engineer at 3am cannot reconstruct what happened to a specific payment"
      ]
    },
    "debugging_capability": "Poor. With only aggregate counters and two histograms, an on-call engineer can see THAT something is wrong but not WHY or for WHICH payments. No way to trace a single payment through the pipeline. During Scenarios A-D, the engineer would see payments_total drop but would need to manually check each dependency to isolate root cause."
  },

  "resilience_assessment": {
    "failure_modes": [
      {
        "scenario": "A: Fraud detection service returns 503 for 5 minutes",
        "handling": "unhandled",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTED IMPACT: 100% payment failure for the full 5 minutes. Every payment is gated on fraud check with no circuit breaker and no fallback. At 2s timeout per request, workers will cycle relatively fast (not pool-exhausting), but every single payment will fail after waiting up to 2s for a 503 response. SURVIVABILITY: Service stays alive but is fully non-functional. ~150 payments fail per minute at moderate load. MUST-HAVE: Add a circuit breaker to the fraud detection call. Consider a fallback policy (e.g., allow payments under $X when fraud service is down, or queue for async fraud review). This is the highest-priority fix."
      },
      {
        "scenario": "B: Database connection pool exhaustion for 30 seconds",
        "handling": "unhandled",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTED IMPACT: Catastrophic cascade. All 20 worker threads will block waiting for a DB connection. Since there is no connection acquire timeout or retry, threads will hang indefinitely (or until a global request timeout, if one exists — not mentioned). New requests queue behind blocked threads. If Stripe charges succeed before DB writes, customers are charged but no transaction record is created — data loss/inconsistency. After pool recovers, queued requests flood DB simultaneously. SURVIVABILITY: Service becomes unresponsive for the full 30s and likely longer due to thundering herd on recovery. MUST-HAVE: (1) Add connection acquire timeout (e.g., 500ms). (2) Add retry with backoff. (3) Increase pool size to match or exceed worker count. (4) Process Stripe charge and DB write atomically or use outbox pattern to prevent charge-without-record."
      },
      {
        "scenario": "C: Stripe API latency increases to 8s for 10 minutes",
        "handling": "unhandled",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTED IMPACT: This is the most dangerous scenario because the circuit breaker will NOT trip — 8s is within the 10s timeout, so Stripe returns successful responses. Each worker thread is now occupied for ~10s (2s fraud + 8s Stripe) instead of the normal ~1-2s. With 20 workers, max throughput drops to ~2 payments/second. At normal load of even 5 req/s, the request queue grows by ~3 req/s. After 10 minutes, ~1,800 requests are queued or timed out. DB connection pool (10) may also exhaust as slow Stripe calls hold workers that then compete for DB connections. SURVIVABILITY: Service stays up but throughput collapses to ~10-20% of normal. Tail latency explodes. Upstream callers may timeout and retry, amplifying the problem. MUST-HAVE: (1) Add an adaptive timeout or latency-based circuit breaker (trip on p99 > threshold, not just failures). (2) Add request admission control / load shedding to reject requests when worker utilization exceeds 80%. (3) Consider reducing Stripe timeout to 5s to fail fast."
      },
      {
        "scenario": "D: Network partition from Stripe for 2 minutes",
        "handling": "partial",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTED IMPACT: First 5 requests timeout after 10s each, then circuit breaker opens. During those first ~50s (5 sequential failures, or faster if concurrent), 5+ workers are blocked for 10s each. Once the circuit breaker opens, subsequent requests fail fast for 60s. After 60s, half-open state lets one request through — it fails (partition still active at 2min), circuit reopens for another 60s. Timeline: 0-50s: slow failure bleeding workers. 50s-2min: fast failure via circuit breaker. 2min+: partition heals, next half-open probe succeeds, circuit closes, recovery. SURVIVABILITY: Moderate. The circuit breaker earns its keep here, but the initial 50s bleed is dangerous — 5 threads blocked for 10s means 25% of worker capacity lost during that window. If combined with any fraud check slowness, cascading failure is likely. NICE-TO-HAVE: Reduce circuit breaker failure threshold from 5 to 3. Add bulkhead isolation so Stripe failures cannot consume all 20 workers."
